        'The second lever is feedback architecture. Most practice environments give you slow, ambiguous, or easily-ignored feedback. You can finish a session and be genuinely uncertain whether anything good happened. Genuine development is dramatically accelerated by feedback that is fast, specific, and impossible to rationalize away. Redesigning your practice so that the feedback loop is tighter — so that you know quickly and clearly whether you solved the problem or didn\'t — is one of the most reliable ways to accelerate development. This sometimes means recording yourself and watching things you don\'t want to see. It sometimes means getting a coach whose explicit job is to surface what you can\'t see. It sometimes means structuring practice so that failure is visibly and immediately consequential rather than deniable.',
        'The third lever is demand level. Not in a "push through the pain" motivational sense — in a structural sense. Raising the demand level of your environment means designing conditions that cannot be successfully navigated with your current skill. It means making the gap between what you can do now and what the environment requires large enough that you must develop to close it. Willpower can temporarily push you to engage above your comfort level. Environmental demand makes that level the unavoidable baseline.',
